\ftnnar\ftnrstcont\sectd\ltrsect\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa120\plain\cf0\up0\f0\fs24Ephrem, Against Heresies, Hymn 22\par\par Translated by Adam C. McCollum\par\par The translation{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Commissioned by Mr. Roger Pearse. The translator welcomes corrections, comments, and queries sent to acmccollum101 AT gmail DOT com.}} was made from the standard edition of the Syriac text: Edmund Beck, \i Des heiligen Ephraem des Syrers Hymnen contra haereses\i0, CSCO 169 // SS 76 (Louvain, 1957). I have added only a very select number of annotations. The hymn is acrostic, that is, the first letter of each stanzas follows the order of the alphabet, and they are so marked (and numbered) below; there is also an extra stanza, beginning with a letter out of order (the eighth, beginning with \i\u353?in\i0), which brings the total number of stanzas to twenty-three instead of the expected twenty-two.\par\par\i To the melody of \ldblquote The infants have been killed\rdblquote\par\i0 1A\par Like the form of the alphabet,\par Which is complete in its parts \emdash\par It lacks no letter,\par Nor does it add another \emdash\par So, too, is the truth written\par In the holy Gospel\par With the letters of the alphabet,\par A perfect measure that admits\par Neither lack nor surplus.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is your image that is in the alphabet!\par\par 2B\par Because Marcion added falsehood,\par The church has removed him and cast him out,\par Valentinus, because he deceived,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  This verb (\i s\u7789?\u257?\i0) is used when commentators and lexicographers explain the etymology of \ldblquote Satan\rdblquote  (\i s\u257?\u7789?\u257?n\u257?\i0).}}\par The Quqite added and perverted,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  This second verb has a range of meanings from \ldblquote destroy\rdblquote  to \ldblquote pervert.\rdblquote}}\par Bardai\u7779?an ornamented his falsehood,\par Mani, who was wholly insane,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  This line rhymes, the last two syllables matching Mani\rquote s name.}}\par A bundle of thorns and thistles.\par May the good one in his mercy turn them\par From wandering into his pasture!\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who is unconcerned about evil ones!\par\par 3G\par Valentinus stole a flock\par From the church and called it by his name;\par The Quqite named one after his name;\par The crafty Bardai\u7779?an stole one;\par And they made the flock a common one.\par Marcion kept his sheep separate,\cf1\par\cf0Mani captured from him,\par One rabid creature bit another,\par They called a flock by their names.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who threw them out of his house!\par\par 4D\par The Arians, because they added and erred;{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  This stanza has no main verb: it seems to be a list of why these groups are considered heretics.}}\par The Aetians, because they were subtle;\par The Paulinians, because they acted perversely;\par The Sabellians, because they acted with guile;\par The Photinians, because they were cunning;\par The Borborians, because they were defiled;\par The Katharaites, because they kept themselves pure;{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The Syriac verb points to the etymology of the sect\rquote s name: \f1\u954?\u945?\u952?\u945?\u961?\u972?\u962? \f0\ldblquote pure.\rdblquote}}\par The Audians, because they were ensnared;\par The Mesallians, because they were unrestrained.\par\i Response: \i0May the good one turn them to his fold!\par\par 5H\par Look! Their hands have lost hold of everything,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  In lines 1, 3, 4, and 6 of this stanza are words having the root \i pl\u7789?\i0.}}\par And they have no handle to grasp,\par They called us Palutians,\par And we escaped that and rejected it.\par Let there be an anathema{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i\u7717?erm\u257?\i0, also in l. 8 and the \i response \i0of this stanza.}} on the one\par Called by the name of Palu\u7789?,\par If not by the name of Christ.\par The furnace of the anathema has exposed them,\par For they do not wish to be banned.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one by whose anathema they have been exposed!\par\par 6W\par Palu\u7789? did not want\par People to name themselves after him,\par And if he we alive, he would curse\par With every anathema{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  In this and the previous line together are the noun \i\u7717?erm\u257? \i0again and the verb from the same root; \ldblquote to anathematize with every anathema\rdblquote  is somewhat awkward in English, and so I have translated the expression as above.}} concerning this,\par Because he was a disciple of the Apostle,\par Who was clothed in suffering and brought to grief\par Concerning the Corinthians, who had left\par The name of Christ and called themselves\par By the names of people.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who has truth!\par\par 7W\par A teacher who does not add\par Anything shameful and hateful\par To the teaching of Christ,\par His disciples are Christians.\par But if he adds a little falsehood,\par He leaves the name of Christ,\par And his disciples call themselves\par By the name of a weed,\par Because falsehood does not match the truth.{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i qu\u353?t\u257?\i0.}}\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who has established us with his truth!{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i\u353?r\u257?r\u257?\i0.}}\par\par 8\u352? (!)\par Smooth to the simple is the way \emdash\par Which is the faith \emdash\par Which{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Grammatically, the subject could be either \ldblquote way\rdblquote  or \ldblquote the faith,\rdblquote  but the former makes the most contextual sense. The following verb is used in the sense of \ldblquote offers.\rdblquote}} extends lodgings and milestones\par From paradise to paradise,\par[From] which the exit [was] through Adam,\par[To] which the return [was] through the robber,\par And investigations, like winding roads,\par Have thrown those who have searched\par From a smooth to a hard place.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who preserves the perfect!\par\par 9\u7716?\par See, my brothers, how [with] the image of the king\par Every coin is struck,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The verb is \i naq\u353?\u257?\i0, a passive participle with feminine subject, that is \i moni\u7789?\u257? \i0(< Latin); Beck\rquote s text has \i kol\u275?h\i0, but we should probably read \i kol\u257?h \i0to agree with that noun.}}\par But a great general is unable\par To stamp a penny with his image.\par When [someone] stamps the image of the king,\par One who stamps it in secret,\par He is either burned or cut off.\par How indeed he has dared, the one who\par Stamped the image of himself instead of [that of] our Lord!\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who stamps us with his name!\par\par 10\u7788?\par Quite despised is gold to our king,\par Who does not stamp his image in money;\par In a human being, the one greater than all,\par Our savior stamps his beauty.\par Who[ever] has believed in the name of God\par Receives the stamp of God,\par But if he has called himself by the name of a human being,\par Then he receives a human stamp,\par Because he despises the living name.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who has chosen us by his names!\par\par 11Y\par Judas, when he stole,\par Was called a disciple,\par And when{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The conjunction \i d- \i0points back to \i kad \i0in the first line of the stanza.}} he was a chief to the left,\par Our Lord called him friend and and taught\par That even the sinful [can be] a disciple.\par As long as he forms no sect, he is a disciple,\par But if he establishes a faction and forms a sect,\par He becomes [the Lord\rquote s] contrary \ldblquote friend.\rdblquote\par Here is his type in Iscariot!\par\i Response: \i0Glory to you from my weakness!\par\par 12K\par Scripture says,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Lit., \ldblquote He writes.\rdblquote}} \ldblquote What king,\par Going to make war\par With another king, his friend\'c9?\rdblquote{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  See Lk 14:31.}}\par It calls them friends, not because they agree,\par But because they are equal\par In the names of royalty,\par Because of which the zealous one{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  I.e. Paul.}} feared\par And did not allow the Corinthians\par To call themselves by the name of a human being.\par\i Response: \i0Appeal to the king against the rebellious!\par\par 13L\par Falsehood clothes the truth{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i qu\u353?t\u257?\i0.}}\par In order to seduce with borrowed beauty,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Beck\rquote s text has the noun \ldblquote beauty\rdblquote  as singular and the adjective \ldblquote borrowed\rdblquote  as plural, and if this is the correct reading, I cannot make good sense of it.}}\par And if an unbeliever confesses [Christ]\par That he might pretend faith in the clothing of a lamb,\par Even Judas to our savior\par Said, \ldblquote Greetings, Rabbi!\rdblquote\par But in his ranks{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i sedr\u257?\i0: presumably a reference to the ranks of soldiers with whom Judas came for Jesus\rquote  arrest.}} he was exposed,\par As, too, was Mani in his deeds,\par Because he had established a faction with his disciples.\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who endured his arrogance!\par\par 14M\par He{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  That is, Mani, as at the end of the previous stanza.}} has been called a false Christ;\par A lying wind{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Of course, the word also means \ldblquote spirit.\rdblquote}} blew in his prophets,\par He broke his body{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The eucharistic language in the translation mirrors that of the original.}} for his disciples,\par And he divided the earth for his heralds\par In the name of our Lord against our Lord;\par And although he tried not to be opposed,\par Openly before many\par He named himself an apostle,\par The Paraclete that existed [only] yesterday!\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who delayed and then captured him!\par\par 15N\par We should know that these things are slight\par To the one who acted boldly, and he{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  \ldblquote These things\rdblquote  in the first line points back to the indictments of the previous stanza and \ldblquote he\rdblquote  here refers to Jesus.}} is of little account to him\par Who opened his mouth for a curse\par And sharpened his tongue for a lie:\par\ldblquote Even the soul in a dog\par Is of divine nature.\rdblquote\par So it was not hard for him if he\par Made himself God,\par Because he had made God dwell in a dog!\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the upright one who did not burn with anger!\par\par 16S\par All the rebellious{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  This reading is from a manuscript reading recorded in Beck\rquote s apparatus and fits the meter and sense well; the word in his text is \ldblquote disturbed,\rdblquote  which fits the meter slightly less well and strikes me as a strange expression here. The readings differ merely in the placement of a dot in Syriac.}} witness\par That there is one yoke upon them,\par One spirit{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Or, as above, \ldblquote wind,\rdblquote  as in stanza 14.}} that has blown in them,\par One error that has spoken in them,\par Those who have contrived and written doctrines,\par Perverse and abominable prohibitions{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i\u7717?erm\u257?\i0; cf. notes 7 and 8 above, where the word is used differently.}}\par That are not from the apostles and prophets!\par And who, my brothers, can remove\par Their mud from within their books?\par\i Response: \i0May the merciful one cleanse them!\par\par 17 \u703?ayin\par About their times let them be asked:\par Which one was older than the other?\par[Is it] that Mani snatches the right of the firstborn?\par Bardai\u7779?an is his predecessor.\par[Is it] that Bardai\u7779?an is made the elder?\par His time is younger than [his] predecessors.\par Marcion is the first thorn,\par The firstborn of sin\rquote s thorny growth,\par The weed that came first and and sprouted.\par\i Response: \i0May the upright one wipe out his growth!\par\par 18P\par Wisely let them be asked:\par From whom have they received this?\par If they have received [it] from us and rejected [it],\par It\rquote s enough for our truth,\par But if they have daringly acted as priests,\par This is enough to reprove them,\par This is sufficient for their shame:\par That anyone is a priest who wants\par to lay his hand on his head!\par\i Response: \i0Confusion of desperation!\par\par 19\u7778?\par The high one inclined to Mt. Sinai\par And covered{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  On the verb here (\i aggen\i0) see S.P. Brock, \i The Luminous Eye\i0, pp. 110-111.}} Moses with his hand;\par Moses put it{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  That is, the authority handed down ultimately from God. Grammatically the \ldblquote it\rdblquote  here is feminine and so agrees with \ldblquote(his) hand\rdblquote  (\i id\u275?h\i0) of the previous line.}} on Aaron\par And it extended to John,\par So our Lord said to him,\par\ldblquote It is righteousness{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i k\u275?nut\u257?\i0.}} that I be baptized by you,\par Lest order{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Syr. \i\u7789?ukk\u257?s\u257?\i0, as again in the last line of this stanza: the meaning is \ldblquote order\rdblquote  in the sense of arrangement and proper structuring, not in that of commandment.}} be lost.\rdblquote\par Our Lord gave it to his disciples,\par And look! Its succession is within our church!\par\i Response: \i0Blessed is the one who has handed down his order!\par\par 20Q\par The voice of our Lord has encompassed them,\par And look! their pledges{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The consonantal form of the word might be read also to mean \ldblquote tents,\rdblquote  but the meter confirms the translation above (i.e. we have here \i me\u353?k\u257?n\u257?\i0, not \i ma\u353?kn\u257?\i0).}} are invalidated,{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Lit. \ldblquote taken away, removed.\rdblquote}}\par[Those] of the Aetians and Arians,\par Sabellians and Katharites,\par Photians and Audians,\par Who had received authority{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  Or perhaps \ldblquote tradition.\rdblquote  This is the word that commonly means \ldblquote hand.\rdblquote  Cf. n. 21 above.}} from our church,\par And cast [that] authority from them\par In [the matter of] the faith that was recorded\par In that splendid council.{\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs24\chftn}{\footnote{\pard\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sa80\plain\cf0\up0\super\f0\fs22\chftn\nosupersub  The Council of Nicaea.}}\par\i Response: \i0Remembered is the king who gathered them!\par\par 21R\par Leaders were in churches,\par And some priests and deacons,\par Others, scribes and readers,\par And one from whom came the covenant.{\plai